// ✅ Question:
// Given an array nums, check whether the array was originally sorted
// in non-decreasing order and then possibly rotated.
//
// An array is considered sorted and rotated if it can be obtained
// by taking a sorted array and rotating it some number of times.
//
// Return true if the array is sorted and rotated, otherwise return false.


// ✅ Approach:
// 1. Traverse the array and count the number of places where
//    the current element is greater than the next element.
//
// 2. If the array was originally sorted and rotated,
//    there can be at most one such position.
//
// 3. Use modulo to compare the last element with the first element
//    to handle the circular rotation condition.
//
// 4. If the count of such positions is more than 1,
//    the array is not sorted and rotated.
//
// 5. Otherwise, return true.


// ✅ Complexity:
//
// Time Complexity: O(N)
// We traverse the array once.
//
// Space Complexity: O(1)
// No extra space is used.


// ✅ Code:
class Solution {
    public boolean check(int[] nums) {
        int c=0;
        for(int i=0;i<nums.length;i++)
        {
            if(nums[i]>nums[(i+1)%nums.length]) c++;
        }
        return c<=1 ? true : false;
    }
}
